    content: `<p>There is a familiar group chat that appears before every wedding. Someone asks what we are all gifting, three people suggest the same appliance, somebody mentions a gift card, and the conversation slowly dies. The friend group wants to give something that feels like <strong>them</strong>, something that matches the years of shared history, and a blender does not exactly capture that.</p><p>Here is an idea that does. Pool together and gift the couple a personalized song about their love story, written and produced as a present from the entire crew.</p><h2>Why a song works as a group gift</h2><p>Friends hold a part of the couple's story that even family sometimes misses. You were there for the nervous texts before the first date. You heard the play by play after the proposal. You know the nickname, the running joke, the disastrous double date that somehow made them stronger. All of that is raw material that no off the shelf gift can use, but a custom song can.</p><p>And practically, splitting a gift makes everything easier:</p><ul><li><strong>It is affordable per person:</strong> divided across the group, each share is tiny.</li><li><strong>It feels enormous:</strong> the couple receives something far grander than any one of you could give alone.</li><li><strong>Everyone contributes a memory:</strong> the gift literally contains pieces of each friendship.</li><li><strong>It does not gather dust:</strong> unlike a physical present, a song gets replayed for years.</li></ul><h2>How to gather the story from everyone</h2><p>The fun part is the collecting. Open a shared note or a quick group call and ask each friend for one memory of the couple. You will be amazed at what surfaces, the moments one of them witnessed that even the couple may have forgotten. Pull out the threads that repeat, the way they always finish each other's sentences, the trip where everyone realised they were endgame, and hand those to the songwriter as the spine of the lyrics.</p><p>You do not need everyone to be poetic. You just need honest little details. The song turns them into something that sounds like it was always meant to be sung.</p><h2>Turning the memories into a finished track</h2><p>This is where it gets surprisingly easy. With <a href="https://www.melodia-songs.com/pricing">Melodia</a>, one person from the group submits the collected story, picks the language and the vibe, whether you want something playful and full of inside jokes or something genuinely tearjerking, and receives a professionally produced song, with options starting at ₹299 split across however many of you chipped in.</p><p>Because it comes in Hindi, Tamil, Telugu, Bengali and more than twenty languages, you can match it to the couple's own world rather than defaulting to English. A few pointers for a great result:</p><ul><li><strong>Decide the tone together:</strong> funny roast or heartfelt tribute, pick one lane so the song stays coherent.</li><li><strong>Choose a representative:</strong> one friend manages the brief so the story stays consistent.</li><li><strong>Keep it a surprise:</strong> the reveal is half the gift.</li></ul><h2>The reveal that steals the wedding</h2><p>Imagine the reception. The friend group gathers the couple, asks for a minute, and plays a song that names them, recounts their story, and is clearly stitched together from everyone who loves them. There is not a dry eye in the squad. The couple realises that their friends did not just show up to celebrate, they made something that will outlive the day.</p><p>That is the gift people talk about for years. Not the value of it, but the thought packed into every line. When the next wedding rolls around and the group chat lights up with the same old question, you will already know the answer.</p><p>Skip the appliance. Give them a song that only their friends could have made.</p>`,
